<subSubSection pageId="89" pageNumber="90" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="89.[123,652,193,1742]" lastBlockId="89.[699,1227,193,275]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">
ETYMOLOGY: The trivial name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" box="[522,651,1719,1742]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cheliferous">
<emphasis box="[522,651,1719,1742]" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">cheliferous</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comes from the Latin noun 
<emphasis box="[1030,1093,193,216]" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">chela</emphasis>
(claw) and ­ 
<emphasis box="[708,781,223,246]" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">ferous</emphasis>
(carry). I refer to the presence of marginal denticles on the phallic plates.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
